<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Exploiting (rambling)</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois.cgi?Scrawny Knoll">Scrawny Knoll</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 4:39 p.m. 25/8/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Exploiting (rambling)<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/forum/common.cgi?read=5797" TARGET=_self>Tired of killing four hundred monsters to gain a level?</A> (Anonymous)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#F4D99F FACE=arial>
<P>Verant calls this exploiting. They consider something exploiting if you take advantage of a bug that allows you to hit a mob without the mob being able to hit you. If you exploit you will be warned a few times and if it continues you will lose your account. I sincerely hope that Verant remembers the most important thing for people should be to have fun. If having fun is grouping, going solo, powergaming, or leveling their customer should be able to do it. I think this game is great and I am totally addicted but I am concerned at the strong arm tactics employed by Verant to make us play a certain way.

<P>&gt; This information is put out as general
<BR>&gt; knowledge. Use it at your own risks as to
<BR>&gt; what the consiquences might be.
<P>&gt; In EverQuest, anyone who's played know's
<BR>&gt; that the game is constantly making you have
<BR>&gt; to gain levels in order to get any fun out
<BR>&gt; of it. Several methods have been used but
<BR>&gt; one of the best so far is to simply block a
<BR>&gt; higher level monster behind an object and
<BR>&gt; then cast magic on it from a distance, never
<BR>&gt; letting it hit you.
<BR>&gt; For players that are in LavaStorm Mountains,
<BR>&gt; you can trap a monster near the entrance to
<BR>&gt; zone to Najena. If you are standing outside
<BR>&gt; the cave entrance, looking towards the door,
<BR>&gt; on the left hand side is a mountain ridge.
<BR>&gt; You can climb the mountain ridge, target a
<BR>&gt; monster, cast a spell upon him, and then run
<BR>&gt; towards the entrance to Najena. If you
<BR>&gt; follow the cliff around and then go through
<BR>&gt; the door about half way up, the monster will
<BR>&gt; continue to travel up, while you are safely
<BR>&gt; inside of the cave. You always have to come
<BR>&gt; from the left side of the door. Now your
<BR>&gt; going to fall and hurt yourself a little,
<BR>&gt; but hitpoints don't matter when you can't
<BR>&gt; get hit. This takes a little practice and
<BR>&gt; you might not get it right away. Have fun
<BR>&gt; with this, as the game was designed for.
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
